      ],
      "nb_lignes": 26,
      "noeuds": [
        {
          "titre": "Anonymous 08/20/14(Wed)00:24:57 No. 5314216 • >5314255 >>5314298",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "My personal recommended syllabus:",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "Read a short history of Ancient Greece (recommend Bury's Greece to the Death of Alexander), or just get an an hour of basic outlining on Wikipedia and similar sites. I'd also recommend Toynbee's On Hellenism but you",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "probably won't find it and it expects a certain level of British schoolboy knowledge of narrative history. You just want to be able to place the thinkers in some sort of context, especially relative to one another. Ultimately what you",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "nost want to understand is that the fifth century is kind of a big deal. Maybe a more in-depth book on Athens in particular (e.g. Kagan's Peloponnesian War), maybe Kagan's Yale course (google it) and its assigned readings",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "maybe look into Teaching Company courses relating to Greece (I recommend Harl). Depends how far you want to go, but knowing the history is vital IMHO.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "Suffer through Homer and Hesiod if you're a completionist. I think Fitzgerald is the best Homer, but use this:",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "https://records.viu.ca/~johnstoi/homer/homertranslations.htm",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "and find your preference. And read this:",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Homeric_Question",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "If you're super completionist, get an anthology or survey book on pre-Classical Athenian writing. Otherwise just wiki Archaic Greek poetry.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "If you're super completionist do the same thing for the pre-Socratic fragments. You won't understand them in their original form and it's not really important to at this point. Just read these at first:",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/presocratics/",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/sophists/",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pre-Socratic_philosophy",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arche",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "They'll fit into the historical context you already know and make a lot more sense. Actual Pre-Socratic fragments are recommended after getting a bit used to philosophy so you can see why they're cool.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "For fifth century history, start with Herodotus, then Thucydides (get Landmark versions of both), then Xenophon (no Landmark yet, get a well-annotated one with maps though). Again look at Kagan's Yale course (for which you",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "read Thucydides), Harl's amazing Teaching Company course on Thucydides, and/or Kagan's book The Peloponnesian War.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "Then this, which you should already know from the history:",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_tragedy",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient Greek_comedy",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "good annotated/commentary versions of Euripides, Sophocles, Aeschylus (the three tragedians), same for Aristophanes (comedy).",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "Then all of Plato in order of writing (very well annotated + use SparkNotes or something). Then Aristotle's major works (ones most talked about today). Plato and Aristotle will be the densest and most difficult but most vital for",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "modern day purposes, as cornerstones of studying philosophy. You will never stop seeing them mentioned, referenced, built upon.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        },
        {
          "titre": "Then the Athenian 4th c. orators mostly for flavour toh. And a book or article on the Hellenistic philosophers or the ones you particularly like.",
          "auteur": null,
          "tier": null
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
